Most of the text content is in Hindi language, also some keywords are mentioned in the English language to better understand the same.  

The goal of the HHD corpus is to provide researchers with a platform which details about different types of diseases, their descriptions, symptoms, treatments and home remedies respectively. As per our knowledge, no such detailed corpus is made available online so far.

HHD corpus is  interpreted and analysed to perform the NER task in the Hindi using vivid NLP techniques. The gazetteer lists for Named Entities (NEs) such as Person, Disease, Consumable and Symptom are also provided. Further, more NEs can be identified and classified from the HHD corpus such as Food, Quantity, Diagnosis etc. by the keen researchers. 

We welcome researchers to enhance and upgrade the corpus to further extent. And also, request them to cite the same whenever it seems worthwhile for their research. I added the historic Honey Production data because we need to go back to a time BEFORE neonics entered our environment.  Neonics pesiticides were used in small amounts in 1994, then in much larger amounts after 2003.  To get a sense of the effects, I've loaded an Overview of the data here:

[Honey and Neonic Charts and Data][1]

Once you're inside the data tool, you can filter any of the variables.  And you can drag and drop variables from the field list to the table.  The Overview dropdown has some other choices.  Have fun!  I'm hoping that somebody out there can work with the data to start to quantity neonics role in the honeybee's struggle. You will see conincidentally, or not, that honeybee yields peaked just before the introduction of neonics.  Is it a coincidence?

You will also note from the data that many states have restricted neonic usage in recent years, though it doesn't seem to have helped hive yields much.  Please note the USGS data is not yet published for 2017, so while charts show zero neonic usage for 2017, it is not true.

In addition, each image has at least one label that pertains to a meal, along with a vector of points that when connected form a shape that outlines the labeled object within the image. Point coordinates are in pixels, beginning at the top left of the image.

In addition some images have labeled grids of varying dimensions which represent the union of all shapes within the image that share a particular label. The proportion of each grid cell that overlaps with this union of shapes is represented as a number between 0 and 1, where null values represent no intersection between grid cell and shapes.

Since the LabelMe project has crowdsourced labeling, the raw labels can be of poor quality. Lots of effort went into curating the labels that were included in this dataset. All told I have worked through 5% of the LabelMe project, and this dataset represents a fraction of that pertaining to meals.

Some statistics:

[{'description': 'This file contains data from my runs with GPS, temperature, and heart rate data.

Each row is a stopwatch stop and a subsequent stopwatch start, with information about both events, as well as cumulative statistics from many windows of time leading up to each stop, as well as overall statistics for a given run in the final columns.

The units used for measurements are kilometers (distance), meters (altitude), degrees Celsius (temperature), kilometers/hour (speed), steps/minute (cadence), seconds (time/duration), and beats/minute (heart rate).

Note that some of the heart rate data is prone to error, especially within the first half mile (0.8 km) of a run. The reasoning is mainly the quality of contact the heart rate band has with the body, which is improved by sweat, water, or some other liquid/gel.

Also note that sometimes temperature or heart rate data is not available. In a few cases, the device was not available for a run. In other cases, it may not have been working for the specific stop/start event.

[{'description': 'This is a dataset of EEG brainwave data that has been processed with our method of statistical extraction

The data was collected from four people (2 male, 2 female) for 60 seconds per state - relaxed, concentrating, neutral. We used a Muse EEG headband which recorded the TP9, AF7, AF8 and TP10 EEG placements via dry electrodes. 

Our method of statistical extraction resampled the data since waves must be mathematically described in a temporal fashion. 

If you would like to use the data in research projects, please cite the following:

J. J. Bird, L. J. Manso, E. P. Ribiero, A. Ekart, and D. R. Faria, A study on mental state classification using eeg-based brain-machine interface,in 9th International Conference on Intelligent Systems, IEEE, 2018.

J.  J.  Bird,  A.  Ekart,  C.  D.  Buckingham,  and  D.  R.  Faria,  Mental emotional  sentiment  classification  with  an  eeg-based  brain-machine interface, in The International Conference on Digital Image and Signal Processing (DISP19), Springer, 2019.

If you would like more detail on the data itself and how this process was carried out, the research paper can be found here:

weight_oz: Total weight in ounces

cals_per_oz: calories per ounce - calories for that day divided by weight in ounces

walk: day included at least one brisk walk of over 20  minutes, 1 = TRUE, 0 = FALSE

run: day included at one short run of 2.5 miles, 1 = TRUE, 0 = FALSE

wine: day finished with at least one large glass of wine when not accompanied by other fluids, 1 = TRUE, 0 = FALSE

prot: day involved what would be considered a high protein diet, 1 = TRUE, 0 = FALSE

weight: signifies day during period of weight-based exercise; includes rest days as part of period, 1 = TRUE, 0 = FALSE

The data was collected from four people (2 male, 2 female) for 60 seconds per state - relaxed, concentrating, neutral. We used a Muse EEG headband which recorded the TP9, AF7, AF8 and TP10 EEG placements via dry electrodes. 

Our method of statistical extraction resampled the data since waves must be mathematically described in a temporal fashion. 

If you would like to use the data in research projects, please cite the following:

J. J. Bird, L. J. Manso, E. P. Ribiero, A. Ekart, and D. R. Faria, A study on mental state classification using eeg-based brain-machine interface,in 9th International Conference on Intelligent Systems, IEEE, 2018.

If you would like more detail on the data itself and how this process was carried out, the research paper can be found here:

With the aim of contributing to the design of evidence-based public health policies in Latin America and the Caribbean and giving special consideration to patient or health service user perspectives, between 2012 and 2014 the Inter-American Development Bank carried out the Primary Care Access, Experience and Coordination Survey in Latin America and the Caribbean, in adult populations in Colombia, Mexico, Brazil, El Salvador, Panama and Jamaica. More detail about the motivations, conceptual framework, and detailed methodology of the survey can be found the publication Desde el paciente: Experiencias de la atencin primaria de salud en Amrica Latina y el Caribe (in Spanish). Primary Healthcare Access, Experience, and Coordination in Latin America and the Caribbean is a dataset of 9,012 observations, that merges the three waves of data collection in the survey, conducted between 2012 and 2014 in: Colombia and Mexico; Brazil and El Salvador; and Panama and Jamaica. The sections below describe the survey methodology, the structure of the questionnaire used for the interviews, and present a detailed codebook of the dataset, generated by Stata 15.1 statistical analysis software.
**Format**
Stata 15.1 data file (.dta).
**Authors**
The dataset was edited by Frederico Guanais and Milagros Anaya.
**Contact Person**
Frederico Guanais, Health Principal Specialist, fredericog@iadb.org. Years of coverage
Cross-sectional data collected between September 2012 and February 2014.
